What kind of sound board are you running? I'm guessing what Jamie is
referring to is known as the "Pin 1 problem" and many (if not most)
inexpensive sound boards exhibit it. There isn't an easy way to fix it
(beyond doing lots of internal modifications you probably don't want to deal
with) so you'll have to find a workaround. If you want to read up on it,
here's the AES (Audio Engineering Society) standard which explains how to
properly ground audio systems:

http://www.aes.org/publications/standards/search.cfm?docID=44
(free download at bottom)

Here is one way to troubleshoot it -- cause the "buzz" to start happening,
and then unplug mic inputs to your sound board one by one. When you find the
culprit, trace that mic cable. My guess is it goes either in a conduit with
lighting cables, or is tied alongside lighting power feeds. Try separating
it and running perpendicular to lighting/power cable where possible.

Whether the light board and sound board are on the same circuit at FOH is
inconsequential here -- the lighting board isn't what is causing it, it's
the dimmers (almost definitely SCRs). It could be improper grounding of the
dimmer rack, which you'll have to get an electrician to fix.

Under no circumstances should you use a "ground lift" adapter on the power
plug for your sound board, amps, or speakers. It may solve the hum, but it
may also kill someone. It's not worth it, and it's illegal.

Hope that helps
-Todd
